Digitalis Dataset

Research question

Population: Patients taking digoxin prior to randomization

Exposure: Discontinuation of digoxin as per randomization

Outcome: Short-term (12 months) risk / hazard ratio of death due to worsened heart failure.

Data cleaning

Missing values

Categorical variables

Some of the categorical variables have missing values. I have dropped the observations with missing values for the variables that are included in the final model.

For the “reason” variable, the missing values means that the patients were still alive. I have recoded it as such.

Continuos variables

klevel and chfdur have missing values. As they are not included in the final model I will leave those observations as is.

Censoring

As we only look at short-term mortality we need to right censor our data, meaning that patients with an event after 365 days will be recoded to not having an event. Additionally, any observational days > 365 will be recoded to 365.

Checking the censoring on a random sample of 100 observations:

Modeling

Informative censoring?

I created a variable called “dropout” to indicate if a patient was censored at < 365.

As shown below the number of patients which dropped out before 365 days from either treatment group was low. Although 50% more dropped out from the continued digoxin group, if it was due to informative censoring the effect on the final estimates is most likely negligible.

Categorical predictors

chfetiol

I have recoded this to follow the primary paper with ischemic vs non-ischemic.

functcls

The counts for class IV are very sparse causing the coefficients in the cox PH model to become very unstable. I have recoded the variable to binary as in the primary paper: class I+II vs class III + IV

Numerical predictors

Correlation matrix

Seems we shouldn’t be too concerned with collinear variables for the numerical predictors.

Checking linearity assumption

We can check the linearity of the individual variables by fitting a model where the only term is a penalized spline of a given variable. We can then use that model to predict the HRs for the observed values and plot the results to check for linearity. Please note that the splines become unstable when the no. of observations are low, which is the case for the lower and upper tail for most of the variables.

Age

I have converted to age groups of 20 years (i.e: 20-40, 40-60 etc.)

Ejection fraction

Seems like there is an approximately linear relationship between ejection fraction and HR. Will keep as continuous variable.

BMI

Seems that BMI is non-linear. Transformed to following scale: < 18.5 = underweight 18.5 -24.9 = normal 25-29.9 = overweight > 30 = obese

Klevel

Recoded as categorical: < 3.5 = “low” 3.5 - 5.1 = “normal” > 5.1 = “high”

Creat

I have recoded as categorical based on the following intervals:

For men, 0.74 to 1.35 mg/dL For women, 0.59 to 1.04 mg/dL

CHF duration

Recoding as > 60 months vs <= 60 months

Chestx

I have recoded as categorical as defined in the primary study: <= 0.55 vs > 0.55

Ilan: A patient had a cardiothoracic ratio of 0.05. Is that possible or an error?

Time dependant covariates

I initially added MI events as a time dependant variable but the number of events were too few making the estimate very unstable. Would have been nice to have included a time dependant covariate as we then would not have to worry about the proportional hazards assumption.

Model Diagnostics

Goodness of fit

The deviance residuals do not raise any suspicions of a poor model fit.

PH assumption

Based on the log(-log) plot and the tests for the Schoenfeld residuals of the final model, we can see that HRs are approximately proportional.
